{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BbTzsaa88cqUqEDiLSf4nR","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 10.5: Workflow Engine Driver Integration\n2\t\n3\tStatus: backlog\n4\t\n5\t<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n6\t\n7\t## Story\n8\t\n9\tAs a developer,\n10\tI want the workflow engine to dispatch tasks through the driver factory instead of calling `dispatchAgent()` directly,\n11\tso that switching drivers is a configuration change, not a code change, and all future drivers work without modifying the engine.\n12\t\n13\t## Acceptance Criteria\n14\t\n15\t1. **Given** the existing `src/lib/workflow-engine.ts`\n16\t   **When** the `dispatchTaskWithResult()` function dispatches a task\n17\t   **Then** it resolves the driver via `getDriver()` from the factory (defaulting to `'claude-code'`)\n18\t   **And** calls `driver.dispatch(opts)` instead of calling `dispatchAgent()` directly\n19\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n20\t\n21\t2. **Given** a `ResolvedTask` without a `driver` field (existing workflows)\n22\t   **When** the engine dispatches the task\n23\t   **Then** it defaults to `getDriver('claude-code')`\n24\t   **And** the workflow executes identically to the pre-refactor behavior\n25\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n26\t\n27\t3. **Given** the engine calls `driver.dispatch(opts)`\n28\t   **When** the dispatch returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`\n29\t   **Then** the engine consumes all `StreamEvent` objects from the iterable\n30\t   **And** captures the `result` event to extract `output`, `sessionId`, and `cost`\n31\t   **And** builds a `DispatchResult`-compatible object from the stream events\n32\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n33\t\n34\t4. **Given** the engine dispatches a task through the driver\n35\t   **When** the model needs to be resolved\n36\t   **Then** it calls `resolveModel(task, agent, driver)` from `model-resolver.ts`\n37\t   **And** passes the resolved model string in `DispatchOpts.model`\n38\t   **Where** `task` is the `ResolvedTask` (which currently has no `model` field — resolves to agent/driver default)\n39\t   **And** `agent` is an object derived from the `SubagentDefinition` (has `model` field)\n40\t   **And** `driver` is the resolved `AgentDriver` instance (has `defaultModel`)\n41\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n42\t\n43\t5. **Given** a driver's `dispatch()` yields a `result` event with an `error` field\n44\t   **When** the engine processes the stream\n45\t   **Then** it maps the error to a `DispatchError` using the `errorCategory` from the result event\n46\t   **And** existing error handling (halt on RATE_LIMIT/NETWORK/SDK_INIT, continue on UNKNOWN) remains unchanged\n47\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n48\t\n49\t6. **Given** a task with `timeout` configured (or the default timeout)\n50\t   **When** the engine builds `DispatchOpts`\n51\t   **Then** it passes the timeout value through to `DispatchOpts.timeout`\n52\t   **And** the driver is responsible for implementing the timeout (the engine does not set its own timer)\n53\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n54\t\n55\t7. **Given** the engine's `dispatchTaskWithResult()` function\n56\t   **When** it builds the `DispatchOpts` for the driver\n57\t   **Then** the opts include: `prompt`, `model` (from resolveModel), `cwd` (projectDir or isolated workspace), `sourceAccess` (from `task.source_access`)\n58\t   **And** `plugins` is set from `task.plugins` if present (forward-compat, currently undefined on ResolvedTask)\n59\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n60\t\n61\t8. **Given** the old `dispatchAgent()` import in `workflow-engine.ts`\n62\t   **When** the refactor is complete\n63\t   **Then** `dispatchAgent` is no longer imported or called from `workflow-engine.ts`\n64\t   **And** the imports instead include `getDriver` from `./agents/drivers/factory.js` and `resolveModel` from `./agents/model-resolver.js`\n65\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n66\t\n67\t9. **Given** the loop block execution in `executeLoopBlock()`\n68\t   **When** loop tasks dispatch through the driver\n69\t   **Then** the driver integration works identically for loop-block tasks and sequential tasks\n70\t   **And** retry prompts (from evaluator findings) are passed through `DispatchOpts.prompt`\n71\t   **And** verdict parsing from per-run tasks still works (output captured from result event)\n72\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n73\t\n74\t10. **Given** `npm run build` is executed\n75\t    **When** the build completes\n76\t    **Then** it succeeds with zero TypeScript errors\n77\t    **And** `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions in existing test suites\n78\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n79\t\n80\t11. **Given** unit tests in `src/lib/__tests__/workflow-engine.test.ts`\n81\t    **When** `npm run test:unit` is executed\n82\t    **Then** tests verify the engine calls `getDriver()` with the correct driver name\n83\t    **And** tests verify the engine calls `driver.dispatch()` with properly constructed `DispatchOpts`\n84\t    **And** tests verify `resolveModel()` is called with `(task, agent, driver)` arguments\n85\t    **And** tests verify the engine consumes `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` and extracts result data\n86\t    **And** tests verify backward compatibility: tasks without `driver` field use `'claude-code'`\n87\t    **And** tests verify error events from the driver stream are mapped to `DispatchError`\n88\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n89\t\n90\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n91\t\n92\t- [ ] Task 1: Refactor `dispatchTaskWithResult()` to use driver factory (AC: #1, #2, #3, #7, #8)\n93\t  - [ ] Remove `import { dispatchAgent, DispatchError } from './agent-dispatch.js'`\n94\t  - [ ] Add `import { getDriver } from './agents/drivers/factory.js'`\n95\t  - [ ] Add `import { resolveModel } from './agents/model-resolver.js'`\n96\t  - [ ] Resolve driver name from `task.driver ?? 'claude-code'` (forward-compat for when ResolvedTask gets a `driver` field)\n97\t  - [ ] Call `getDriver(driverName)` to get the driver instance\n98\t  - [ ] Build `DispatchOpts` with: prompt, model (from resolveModel), cwd, sourceAccess, plugins, timeout\n99\t  - [ ] Call `driver.dispatch(opts)` and consume the `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`\n100\t  - [ ] Extract output text, sessionId, and cost from the `result` event\n101\t  - [ ] Return a `DispatchResult`-compatible object constructed from stream data\n102\t\n103\t- [ ] Task 2: Integrate `resolveModel()` into dispatch flow (AC: #4)\n104\t  - [ ] Call `resolveModel(task, agentAsModelSource, driver)` before dispatch\n105\t  - [ ] Build `agentAsModelSource` from `SubagentDefinition.model` (map to `{ model: definition.model }`)\n106\t  - [ ] Pass resolved model in `DispatchOpts.model`\n107\t\n108\t- [ ] Task 3: Map driver error events to DispatchError (AC: #5)\n109\t  - [ ] When the result event has an `error` field, throw a `DispatchError`\n110\t  - [ ] Map `errorCategory` from the result event to `DispatchErrorCode` (RATE_LIMIT, NETWORK map directly; AUTH/TIMEOUT map to UNKNOWN for now since DispatchErrorCode doesn't have them; or add them)\n111\t  - [ ] Preserve existing halt-on-critical-error logic\n112\t\n113\t- [ ] Task 4: Handle timeout pass-through (AC: #6)\n114\t  - [ ] Pass `task.max_budget_usd` or timeout config through `DispatchOpts.timeout` if available\n115\t  - [ ] Remove any engine-level timeout handling for driver calls (driver owns timeout now)\n116\t\n117\t- [ ] Task 5: Verify loop block integration (AC: #9)\n118\t  - [ ] Confirm `executeLoopBlock()` uses the same dispatch path (it calls `dispatchTask()` / `dispatchTaskWithResult()`)\n119\t  - [ ] Verify retry prompts pass through correctly\n120\t  - [ ] Verify verdict parsing still works from captured output\n121\t\n122\t- [ ] Task 6: Write unit tests (AC: #10, #11)\n123\t  - [ ] Mock `getDriver()` to return a fake `AgentDriver` with a controlled `dispatch()` async generator\n124\t  - [ ] Mock `resolveModel()` to return a known model string\n125\t  - [ ] Test: engine calls `getDriver('claude-code')` when task has no driver field\n126\t  - [ ] Test: engine calls `driver.dispatch()` with correct `DispatchOpts` shape\n127\t  - [ ] Test: engine extracts output, sessionId, cost from result event\n128\t  - [ ] Test: engine maps error result events to `DispatchError`\n129\t  - [ ] Test: `resolveModel()` is called with correct arguments\n130\t  - [ ] Test: existing sequential + loop block tests still pass\n131\t  - [ ] Verify `npm run build` succeeds\n132\t  - [ ] Verify `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions\n133\t\n134\t## Dev Notes\n135\t\n136\t### Architecture Compliance\n137\t\n138\tThis story implements the \"Workflow Engine Driver Integration\" from Epic 1 (Story 1.5) in `epics-multi-framework.md`. It is the keystone story that connects the driver abstraction (stories 10-1 through 10-4) to the existing workflow engine.\n139\t\n140\tKey architecture decisions honored:\n141\t- **Decision 1 (Driver Interface):** Engine consumes `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from `driver.dispatch()` — framework-agnostic\n142\t- **Decision 4 (Model Resolution):** Engine calls `resolveModel(task, agent, driver)` before every dispatch\n143\t- **Factory pattern:** Engine uses `getDriver(name)` — no direct driver instantiation\n144\t\n145\t### Current State of the Codebase\n146\t\n147\t- **`workflow-engine.ts`** currently imports and calls `dispatchAgent()` from `agent-dispatch.ts`. This is the old dispatch path — a direct Agent SDK call that returns `DispatchResult` (sessionId, success, durationMs, output).\n148\t- **`dispatchTaskWithResult()`** is the single internal function that all dispatch paths go through (both `dispatchTask()` and loop block execution). Refactoring this one function is sufficient.\n149\t- **`agent-dispatch.ts`** will NOT be deleted — it may still be used by other code paths (e.g., direct CLI invocation outside the workflow engine). But `workflow-engine.ts` should no longer import it.\n150\t- **`DispatchError`** is defined in `agent-dispatch.ts`. The engine currently catches `DispatchError` instances to decide halt vs continue. The refactored engine must still throw/catch `DispatchError` — either by continuing to import the class from `agent-dispatch.ts` (acceptable) or by re-creating the error from driver stream events.\n151\t- **`ResolvedTask`** does NOT currently have a `driver` field or a `model` field. Those come in story 11-1 (Workflow Schema Extension). The engine must use `(task as { driver?: string }).driver ?? 'claude-code'` or similar forward-compatible access.\n152\t- **`SubagentDefinition`** has a `model` field (currently hardcoded to `'claude-sonnet-4-20250514'`). This is used as the agent-level input to `resolveModel()`.\n153\t\n154\t### Stream Consumption Pattern\n155\t\n156\tThe driver's `dispatch()` returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`. The engine must consume it to completion, collecting:\n157\t\n158\t```typescript\n159\tlet output = '';\n160\tlet sessionId = '';\n161\tlet cost = 0;\n162\t\n163\tfor await (const event of driver.dispatch(opts)) {\n164\t  if (event.type === 'text') {\n165\t    output += event.text;\n166\t  }\n167\t  if (event.type === 'result') {\n168\t    sessionId = event.sessionId;\n169\t    cost = event.cost;\n170\t    if (event.error) {\n171\t      // Map to DispatchError and throw\n172\t    }\n173\t  }\n174\t}\n175\t```\n176\t\n177\tThis replaces the old `dispatchAgent()` call which returned `DispatchResult` directly.\n178\t\n179\t### DispatchError Handling Strategy\n180\t\n181\tTwo options for DispatchError:\n182\t1. **Keep importing `DispatchError` from `agent-dispatch.ts`** — the class is framework-agnostic and only carries a code, message, agentName, and cause. No reason to duplicate it.\n183\t2. **Move `DispatchError` to a shared types file** — cleaner long-term but out of scope for this story.\n184\t\n185\tRecommended: option 1 (keep importing from agent-dispatch). The `DispatchError` import stays; only `dispatchAgent` import is removed.\n186\t\n187\t### What NOT to Do\n188\t\n189\t- Do NOT modify `agent-dispatch.ts` — it remains as-is for backward compat\n190\t- Do NOT add `driver` or `model` fields to `ResolvedTask` — that's story 11-1\n191\t- Do NOT modify `ClaudeCodeDriver` or `factory.ts` — they are done\n192\t- Do NOT modify `model-resolver.ts` — it is done\n193\t- Do NOT modify `workflow-parser.ts` or `workflow.schema.json` — schema extension is story 11-1\n194\t- Do NOT delete `agent-dispatch.ts` — other code paths may still use it\n195\t- Do NOT add driver registration to `workflow-engine.ts` — drivers are registered at application startup (likely in the CLI entry point)\n196\t\n197\t### Driver Registration Prerequisite\n198\t\n199\tThe driver factory must have drivers registered before the engine runs. This likely happens in the CLI entry point (e.g., `src/commands/run.ts` or similar). If no registration exists yet, the engine tests must mock `getDriver()` or call `registerDriver()` in test setup. The engine itself does NOT register drivers.\n200\t\n201\t### Testing Patterns\n202\t\n203\t- Follow existing Vitest patterns in `src/lib/__tests__/`\n204\t- Mock `getDriver` from `./agents/drivers/factory.js` using `vi.mock()`\n205\t- Create a mock `AgentDriver` that returns a controlled async generator from `dispatch()`\n206\t- Mock `resolveModel` to return a fixed string\n207\t- Existing workflow-engine tests (if any) should continue to pass — update their mocks to work with the new dispatch path\n208\t- Use `vi.spyOn` to verify `getDriver` and `resolveModel` are called with expected arguments\n209\t\n210\t### References\n211\t\n212\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-multi-framework.md#Decision 1: Driver Interface Design]\n213\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-multi-framework.md#Decision 4: Model Resolution]\n214\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-multi-framework.md#Story 1.5: Workflow Engine Driver Integration]\n215\t- [Source: src/lib/workflow-engine.ts — dispatchTaskWithResult() function]\n216\t- [Source: src/lib/agent-dispatch.ts — dispatchAgent(), DispatchError]\n217\t- [Source: src/lib/agents/drivers/factory.ts — getDriver()]\n218\t- [Source: src/lib/agents/model-resolver.ts — resolveModel()]\n219\t- [Source: src/lib/agents/types.ts — AgentDriver, DispatchOpts]\n220\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f83470b7-c271-483e-ae93-7fe9bce4b683","uuid":"a59feb11-ae38-4328-b369-f771ffc00d19","timestamp":"2026-04-03T07:41:03.355Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/10-5-workflow-engine-driver-integration.md","content":"# Story 10.5: Workflow Engine Driver Integration\n\nStatus: backlog\n\n<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n\n## Story\n\nAs a developer,\nI want the workflow engine to dispatch tasks through the driver factory instead of calling `dispatchAgent()` directly,\nso that switching drivers is a configuration change, not a code change, and all future drivers work without modifying the engine.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. **Given** the existing `src/lib/workflow-engine.ts`\n   **When** the `dispatchTaskWithResult()` function dispatches a task\n   **Then** it resolves the driver via `getDriver()` from the factory (defaulting to `'claude-code'`)\n   **And** calls `driver.dispatch(opts)` instead of calling `dispatchAgent()` directly\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n2. **Given** a `ResolvedTask` without a `driver` field (existing workflows)\n   **When** the engine dispatches the task\n   **Then** it defaults to `getDriver('claude-code')`\n   **And** the workflow executes identically to the pre-refactor behavior\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n3. **Given** the engine calls `driver.dispatch(opts)`\n   **When** the dispatch returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`\n   **Then** the engine consumes all `StreamEvent` objects from the iterable\n   **And** captures the `result` event to extract `output`, `sessionId`, and `cost`\n   **And** builds a `DispatchResult`-compatible object from the stream events\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n4. **Given** the engine dispatches a task through the driver\n   **When** the model needs to be resolved\n   **Then** it calls `resolveModel(task, agent, driver)` from `model-resolver.ts`\n   **And** passes the resolved model string in `DispatchOpts.model`\n   **Where** `task` is the `ResolvedTask` (which currently has no `model` field — resolves to agent/driver default)\n   **And** `agent` is an object derived from the `SubagentDefinition` (has `model` field)\n   **And** `driver` is the resolved `AgentDriver` instance (has `defaultModel`)\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n5. **Given** a driver's `dispatch()` yields a `result` event with an `error` field\n   **When** the engine processes the stream\n   **Then** it maps the error to a `DispatchError` using the `errorCategory` from the result event\n   **And** existing error handling (halt on RATE_LIMIT/NETWORK/SDK_INIT, continue on UNKNOWN) remains unchanged\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n6. **Given** a task with `timeout` configured (or the default timeout)\n   **When** the engine builds `DispatchOpts`\n   **Then** it passes the timeout value through to `DispatchOpts.timeout`\n   **And** the driver is responsible for implementing the timeout (the engine does not set its own timer)\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n7. **Given** the engine's `dispatchTaskWithResult()` function\n   **When** it builds the `DispatchOpts` for the driver\n   **Then** the opts include: `prompt`, `model` (from resolveModel), `cwd` (projectDir or isolated workspace), `sourceAccess` (from `task.source_access`)\n   **And** `plugins` is set from `task.plugins` if present (forward-compat, currently undefined on ResolvedTask)\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n8. **Given** the old `dispatchAgent()` import in `workflow-engine.ts`\n   **When** the refactor is complete\n   **Then** `dispatchAgent` is no longer imported or called from `workflow-engine.ts`\n   **And** the imports instead include `getDriver` from `./agents/drivers/factory.js` and `resolveModel` from `./agents/model-resolver.js`\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n9. **Given** the loop block execution in `executeLoopBlock()`\n   **When** loop tasks dispatch through the driver\n   **Then** the driver integration works identically for loop-block tasks and sequential tasks\n   **And** retry prompts (from evaluator findings) are passed through `DispatchOpts.prompt`\n   **And** verdict parsing from per-run tasks still works (output captured from result event)\n   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n10. **Given** `npm run build` is executed\n    **When** the build completes\n    **Then** it succeeds with zero TypeScript errors\n    **And** `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions in existing test suites\n    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n11. **Given** unit tests in `src/lib/__tests__/workflow-engine.test.ts`\n    **When** `npm run test:unit` is executed\n    **Then** tests verify the engine calls `getDriver()` with the correct driver name\n    **And** tests verify the engine calls `driver.dispatch()` with properly constructed `DispatchOpts`\n    **And** tests verify `resolveModel()` is called with `(task, agent, driver)` arguments\n    **And** tests verify the engine consumes `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` and extracts result data\n    **And** tests verify backward compatibility: tasks without `driver` field use `'claude-code'`\n    **And** tests verify error events from the driver stream are mapped to `DispatchError`\n    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n## Tasks / Subtasks\n\n- [ ] Task 1: Refactor `dispatchTaskWithResult()` to use driver factory (AC: #1, #2, #3, #7, #8)\n  - [ ] Remove `import { dispatchAgent, DispatchError } from './agent-dispatch.js'`\n  - [ ] Add `import { getDriver } from './agents/drivers/factory.js'`\n  - [ ] Add `import { resolveModel } from './agents/model-resolver.js'`\n  - [ ] Resolve driver name from `task.driver ?? 'claude-code'` (forward-compat for when ResolvedTask gets a `driver` field)\n  - [ ] Call `getDriver(driverName)` to get the driver instance\n  - [ ] Build `DispatchOpts` with: prompt, model (from resolveModel), cwd, sourceAccess, plugins, timeout\n  - [ ] Call `driver.dispatch(opts)` and consume the `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`\n  - [ ] Extract output text, sessionId, and cost from the `result` event\n  - [ ] Return a `DispatchResult`-compatible object constructed from stream data\n\n- [ ] Task 2: Integrate `resolveModel()` into dispatch flow (AC: #4)\n  - [ ] Call `resolveModel(task, agentAsModelSource, driver)` before dispatch\n  - [ ] Build `agentAsModelSource` from `SubagentDefinition.model` (map to `{ model: definition.model }`)\n  - [ ] Pass resolved model in `DispatchOpts.model`\n\n- [ ] Task 3: Map driver error events to DispatchError (AC: #5)\n  - [ ] When the result event has an `error` field, throw a `DispatchError`\n  - [ ] Map `errorCategory` from the result event to `DispatchErrorCode` (RATE_LIMIT, NETWORK map directly; AUTH/TIMEOUT map to UNKNOWN for now since DispatchErrorCode doesn't have them; or add them)\n  - [ ] Preserve existing halt-on-critical-error logic\n\n- [ ] Task 4: Handle timeout pass-through (AC: #6)\n  - [ ] Pass `task.max_budget_usd` or timeout config through `DispatchOpts.timeout` if available\n  - [ ] Remove any engine-level timeout handling for driver calls (driver owns timeout now)\n\n- [ ] Task 5: Verify loop block integration (AC: #9)\n  - [ ] Confirm `executeLoopBlock()` uses the same dispatch path (it calls `dispatchTask()` / `dispatchTaskWithResult()`)\n  - [ ] Verify retry prompts pass through correctly\n  - [ ] Verify verdict parsing still works from captured output\n\n- [ ] Task 6: Write unit tests (AC: #10, #11)\n  - [ ] Mock `getDriver()` to return a fake `AgentDriver` with a controlled `dispatch()` async generator\n  - [ ] Mock `resolveModel()` to return a known model string\n  - [ ] Test: engine calls `getDriver('claude-code')` when task has no driver field\n  - [ ] Test: engine calls `driver.dispatch()` with correct `DispatchOpts` shape\n  - [ ] Test: engine extracts output, sessionId, cost from result event\n  - [ ] Test: engine maps error result events to `DispatchError`\n  - [ ] Test: `resolveModel()` is called with correct arguments\n  - [ ] Test: existing sequential + loop block tests still pass\n  - [ ] Verify `npm run build` succeeds\n  - [ ] Verify `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions\n\n## Dev Notes\n\n### Architecture Compliance\n\nThis story implements the \"Workflow Engine Driver Integration\" from Epic 1 (Story 1.5) in `epics-multi-framework.md`. It is the keystone story that connects the driver abstraction (stories 10-1 through 10-4) to the existing workflow engine.\n\nKey architecture decisions honored:\n- **Decision 1 (Driver Interface):** Engine consumes `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from `driver.dispatch()` — framework-agnostic\n- **Decision 4 (Model Resolution):** Engine calls `resolveModel(task, agent, driver)` before every dispatch\n- **Factory pattern:** Engine uses `getDriver(name)` — no direct driver instantiation\n\n### Current State of the Codebase\n\n- **`workflow-engine.ts`** currently imports and calls `dispatchAgent()` from `agent-dispatch.ts`. This is the old dispatch path — a direct Agent SDK call that returns `DispatchResult` (sessionId, success, durationMs, output).\n- **`dispatchTaskWithResult()`** is the single internal function that all dispatch paths go through (both `dispatchTask()` and loop block execution). Refactoring this one function is sufficient.\n- **`agent-dispatch.ts`** will NOT be deleted — it may still be used by other code paths (e.g., direct CLI invocation outside the workflow engine). But `workflow-engine.ts` should no longer import it.\n- **`DispatchError`** is defined in `agent-dispatch.ts`. The engine currently catches `DispatchError` instances to decide halt vs continue. The refactored engine must still throw/catch `DispatchError` — either by continuing to import the class from `agent-dispatch.ts` (acceptable) or by re-creating the error from driver stream events.\n- **`ResolvedTask`** does NOT currently have a `driver` field or a `model` field. Those come in story 11-1 (Workflow Schema Extension). The engine must use `(task as { driver?: string }).driver ?? 'claude-code'` or similar forward-compatible access.\n- **`SubagentDefinition`** has a `model` field (currently hardcoded to `'claude-sonnet-4-20250514'`). This is used as the agent-level input to `resolveModel()`.\n\n### Stream Consumption Pattern\n\nThe driver's `dispatch()` returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`. The engine must consume it to completion, collecting:\n\n```typescript\nlet output = '';\nlet sessionId = '';\nlet cost = 0;\n\nfor await (const event of driver.dispatch(opts)) {\n  if (event.type === 'text') {\n    output += event.text;\n  }\n  if (event.type === 'result') {\n    sessionId = event.sessionId;\n    cost = event.cost;\n    if (event.error) {\n      // Map to DispatchError and throw\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis replaces the old `dispatchAgent()` call which returned `DispatchResult` directly.\n\n### DispatchError Handling Strategy\n\nTwo options for DispatchError:\n1. **Keep importing `DispatchError` from `agent-dispatch.ts`** — the class is framework-agnostic and only carries a code, message, agentName, and cause. No reason to duplicate it.\n2. **Move `DispatchError` to a shared types file** — cleaner long-term but out of scope for this story.\n\nRecommended: option 1 (keep importing from agent-dispatch). The `DispatchError` import stays; only `dispatchAgent` import is removed.\n\n### What NOT to Do\n\n- Do NOT modify `agent-dispatch.ts` — it remains as-is for backward compat\n- Do NOT add `driver` or `model` fields to `ResolvedTask` — that's story 11-1\n- Do NOT modify `ClaudeCodeDriver` or `factory.ts` — they are done\n- Do NOT modify `model-resolver.ts` — it is done\n- Do NOT modify `workflow-parser.ts` or `workflow.schema.json` — schema extension is story 11-1\n- Do NOT delete `agent-dispatch.ts` — other code paths may still use it\n- Do NOT add driver registration to `workflow-engine.ts` — drivers are registered at application startup (likely in the CLI entry point)\n\n### Driver Registration Prerequisite\n\nThe driver factory must have drivers registered before the engine runs. This likely happens in the CLI entry point (e.g., `src/commands/run.ts` or similar). If no registration exists yet, the engine tests must mock `getDriver()` or call `registerDriver()` in test setup. The engine itself does NOT register drivers.\n\n### Testing Patterns\n\n- Follow existing Vitest patterns in `src/lib/__tests__/`\n- Mock `getDriver` from `./agents/drivers/factory.js` using `vi.mock()`\n- Create a mock `AgentDriver` that returns a controlled async generator from `dispatch()`\n- Mock `resolveModel` to return a fixed string\n- Existing workflow-engine tests (if any) should continue to pass — update their mocks to work with the new dispatch path\n- Use `vi.spyOn` to verify `getDriver` and `resolveModel` are called with expected arguments\n\n### References\n\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-multi-framework.md#Decision 1: Driver Interface Design]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-multi-framework.md#Decision 4: Model Resolution]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-multi-framework.md#Story 1.5: Workflow Engine Driver Integration]\n- [Source: src/lib/workflow-engine.ts — dispatchTaskWithResult() function]\n- [Source: src/lib/agent-dispatch.ts — dispatchAgent(), DispatchError]\n- [Source: src/lib/agents/drivers/factory.ts — getDriver()]\n- [Source: src/lib/agents/model-resolver.ts — resolveModel()]\n- [Source: src/lib/agents/types.ts — AgentDriver, DispatchOpts]\n","numLines":220,"startLine":1,"totalLines":220}}}
